  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-cylindrical">
    <title>Cylindrical Coordinates</title>
    
    <p>
      We have encountered two different coordinate systems in <m>\R^2</m>, rectangular and polar coordinates, and seen how polar coordinates form a convenient alternative in certain situations. In a similar way, there are two more coordinate systems in <m>\R^3</m> that come from different ideas of rotational measurement. 
      As we saw earlier, polar coordiantes will be an advantageous coordinate system when considering points/graphs/regions which have rotationally symmetric properties with respect to the origin. Given that we are already familiar with the Cartesian coordinate system for <m>\R^3</m> (from <xref ref="S-Precalc-3Dcoord" />), we will investigate cylindrical and spherical coordinates as ways to use angular measurements as part of our description for location in three dimensional space. 
    </p>
    <p>
      <term>Cylindrical coordinates</term> are a coordinate system for <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> that consists of using polar coordinates, <m>r</m> and <m>\theta</m>, in place of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> coordinates. Cylindrical coordinates are given in the order of <m>(r,\theta,z)</m> and can be described as <q>polar plus z</q>. The <m>z</m> coordinate is measured the same way as in rectangular coordinates (signed distance above or below the <m>xy</m>-plane) and polar coordinates are measured as a projection of the 3D point onto the <m>xy</m>-plane. To convert between rectangular and cylindrical coordinates, we use the same conversion equations as between rectangular and polar coordinates (in 2D).
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="cylcoorddefn">
      <caption>A plot of point <m>P</m> with <m>y</m>, <m>z</m>, and <m>r</m> labeled</caption>
      <interactive title="interactive-cylcoorddefn" platform="sage" width="75%" aspect="1:1">
        <slate surface="sage">
          from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
          var('s,t')
          scale=4
          et=arctan(2)
          plot12=axes(scale,1,color="black",frame=False)+text3d("x",(scale+0.5,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,scale+0.5,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,scale+0.5),fontsize=30)
          plot12+=parametric_plot3d((s,t,0),(s,-1,3),(t,-1,3),opacity=0.15,color="gray",aspect_ratio=1,mesh=True,plot_points=5)
          plot12+=parametric_plot3d((0.5*cos(t),0.5*sin(t),0),(t,0,et),color="blue",thickness=2)
          plot12+=arrow((0.5*cos(et-0.1),0.5*sin(et-0.1),0),(0.5*cos(et),0.5*sin(et),0),color="blue",width=10)
          plot12+=parametric_plot3d((t,2*t,0),(t,0,1),color="red",thickness=2)
          plot12+=line([(1,2,0),(1,2,2.5)],color="green",thickness=2)
          plot12+=point3d((1,2,2.5),color="black",size=30)
          plot12+=text3d("P=(r,\u03B8,z)",(1,2,3),fontsize=30,color="black")
          plot12+=text3d("\u03B8",(1.5,0.5,0),color="blue",fontsize=25)
          plot12+=text3d("r",(0.5,1.5,0.75),color="red",fontsize=25)
          plot12+=text3d("z",(1.25,2.5,1.5),color="green",fontsize=25)
          show(plot12,viewpoint=[[-0.4306,-0.5735,-0.6969],124.76],camera_position=[12.851,4.9751,4.488])
        </slate>
      </interactive>
    </figure>
    <!-- <figure xml:id="Cylindrical_coords_def">
      <caption>The cylindrical coordinates of a point</caption>
        <image width="55%" source="images/fig_11_8_cylindrical"/>
    </figure> -->

    <assemblage xml:id="Cartesian-cylindrical">
      <title>Converting between Rectangular and Cylindrical coordinates</title>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <title>Converting from cylindrical to rectangular</title>
          <p>
            If we are given the cylindrical coordinates <m>(r,\theta,z)</m> of a point <m>P</m>, then the rectangular coordinates <m>(x,y,z)</m> of <m>P</m> satisfy
            <me>
            x = r \cos(\theta) \quad \quad y = r \sin(\theta) \quad \quad  z = z
            </me>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <title>Converting from Rectangular to Cylindrical</title>
          <p>
            If we are given the Rectangular coordinates <m>(x,y,z)</m> of a point <m>P</m>, then the Cylindrical coordinates <m>(r,\theta,z)</m> of <m>P</m> satisfy
            <me>
            r^2  = x^2  + y^2 \quad \quad  \tan(\theta) = \frac{y}{x} \quad \quad  z = z
            </me>
            assuming <m> x \neq 0</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    </assemblage>
    <example>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For our first example, we will look at the point with cylindrical coordinates <m>(r,\theta,z)=(\sqrt{5},\frac{3\pi}{4},-2)</m>. This point is shown in the figure below with the measurements of the cylindrical coordinates.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="cylex1">
            <caption>A plot of <m>(r,\theta,z)=(\sqrt{5},\frac{3\pi}{4},-2)</m></caption>
              <interactive title="interactive-cylex1" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
                <slate surface="sage">
                  from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
                  var('s,t')
                  scale=3.5
                  plot15=axes(scale,1,color="black",frame=False)+text3d("x",(scale+0.5,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,scale+0.5,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,scale+0.5),fontsize=30)
                  plot15+=line([(0,0,0),(-3,0,0)],color="gray")
                  plot15+=point3d((-sqrt(10)/2,sqrt(10)/2,-2),size=25,color="black")+line([(-sqrt(10)/2,sqrt(10)/2,-2),(-sqrt(10)/2,sqrt(10)/2,0)],color="green",thickness=2)
                  plot15+=text3d("-2",(-sqrt(10)/2+0.5,2,-1),color="green",fontsize=25)
                  plot15+=line([(-sqrt(10)/2,sqrt(10)/2,0),(0,0,0)],color="blue",thickness=2)+text3d("r",(-sqrt(10)/3,sqrt(10)/3-0.6,0),color="blue",fontsize=25)
                  plot15+=parametric_plot3d((cos(t),sin(t),0),(t,0, 0.75*pi),color="red",thickness=2)+text3d("\u03B8",(1,1,0),color="red",fontsize=25)
                  plot15+=arrow3d((cos(0.75*pi-0.1),sin(0.75*pi-0.1),0),(-1/sqrt(2),1/sqrt(2),0),color="red",width=5)
                  plot15+=parametric_plot3d((s,t,0),(s,-3,3),(t,-3,3),opacity=0.05,color="gray",aspect_ratio=1,mesh=True,plot_points=5)
                  show(plot15,aspect_ratio=1,viewpoint=[[0.076,-0.5053,-0.8596],194.73],camera_position=[-2.8466,11.7913,6.6115])
                </slate>
              </interactive>
          </figure>
          <p>
            To convert our cylindrical coordinates to rectangular, we can use <m>x = r \cos(\theta)</m> and <m>y = r \sin(\theta)</m> to get rectangular coordinates of <m>(x,y,z)= (-\frac{\sqrt{10}}{2},\frac{\sqrt{10}}{2},-2)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            In this example, we want to find cylindrical coordinates for the point with rectangular coordinates <m>(x,y,z)=(-2,1,2)</m>. Remember that just as the polar coordinates of a point in 2D are not unique, the cylindrical coordinates of a point in 3D will not be unique. 
          </p>
          <p>
            Using our conversion equations from rectangular to cylindrical, we get <m>r^2=(-2)^2+(1)^2=5</m> and <m>\tan(\theta)= \frac{1}{-2}</m>. Remember that we must interpret the angle <em>and</em> our choice of <m>r</m> to make sure our coordinates describe a point in the second octant. In particular, we will choose a positive <m>r</m> value of <m>\sqrt{5}</m> which means we will need to select an angle of <m>\arctan(-\frac{1}{2})+\pi</m>. 
          </p>
          <p>  
            Alterntatively, we can use <m>\cos(\theta)=\frac{x}{r}</m> since <m>\arccos</m> will give an output of an angle in the first or second quadrants. You can verify that <m>\theta = \arctan(-\frac{1}{2})+\pi = \arccos(-\frac{2}{\sqrt{5}})</m>. So rectangular coordinates <m>(x,y,z)=(-2,1,2)</m> will coorespond to cylindrical coordinates of <m>(r,\theta,z)= (\sqrt{5},\arctan(-\frac{1}{2})+\pi,2)</m> or <m>(r,\theta,z)= (\sqrt{5},\arccos(-\frac{2}{\sqrt{5}},2) )</m>.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="cylex2">
            <caption>A plot of <m>(x,y,z)=(-2,1,2)</m></caption>
              <interactive title="interactive-cylex2" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
                <slate surface="sage">
                  from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
                  var('s,t')
                  scale=3
                  a=arccos(-2/sqrt(5))
                  plot16=axes(scale,1,color="black",frame=False)+text3d("x",(scale+0.5,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,scale+0.5,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,scale+0.5),fontsize=30)
                  plot16+=parametric_plot3d((s,t,0),(s,-3,3),(t,-3,3),opacity=0.05,color="gray",aspect_ratio=1,mesh=True,plot_points=5)
                  plot16+=point3d((-2,1,2),size=25,color="black")+line([(-2,1,2),(-2,1,0)],color="green",thickness=2)+text3d("2",(-2.25,1,1.35),color="green",fontsize=25)
                  plot16+=line([(-2,1,0),(-2,0,0)],color="red",thickness=2)+text3d("1",(-2.5,0.5,0.25),color="red",fontsize=25)
                  plot16+=line([(0,0,0),(-2,0,0)],color="blue",thickness=2)+text3d("-2",(-1,0,0.25),color="blue",fontsize=25)
                  plot16+=line([(0,0,0),(-2,1,0)],color="purple",thickness=2)+text3d("r",(-1.5,1.5,0.25),color="purple",fontsize=25)
                  plot16+=parametric_plot3d((cos(t),sin(t),0),(t,0,a),color="orange",thickness=2)+text3d("\u03B8",(0.75,1.25,0.25),color="orange",fontsize=25)
                  plot16+=arrow3d((cos(a-.1),sin(a-0.1),0),(cos(a),sin(a),0),color="orange",width=3)
                  show(plot16,aspect_ratio=1,viewpoint=[[0.1647,-0.5839,-0.7949],205.27],camera_position=[-5.5009,7.7206,3.466])
                </slate>
              </interactive>
          </figure>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            In our earlier work on polar coordinates, we saw how the graph of <m>\theta=2</m> will be a line with slope <m>\tan(2)</m>. If we consider only positive <m>r</m> coordinates then we get a ray with an angle of 2 radians from the positive <m>x</m>-axis. If we wanted to consider the graph of <m>\theta=2</m> using cylindrical coordinates (in 3D), then we get a plane that contains the <m>z</m>-axis and goes in the <m>\theta=2</m> direction. This is a cylinder surface with the line given by <m>y=tan(2) x</m> as the generating curve and rulings parallel to the <m>x</m>-axis.  
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="cylex3">
            <caption>A plot of <m>\theta=2</m> with positive <m>r</m> values in blue and negative <m>r</m> values in green</caption>
              <interactive title="interactive-cylex3" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
                <slate surface="sage">
                  from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
                  var('s,t')
                  scale=3.5
                  a=pi+2
                  plot17=axes(scale,2,color="black",frame=False)+text3d("x",(scale+0.5,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,scale+0.5,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,scale+0.5),fontsize=30)
                  plot17+=parametric_plot3d((s,tan(2)*s,t),(t,-scale,scale),(s,-2,0),color="blue",opacity=.25,mesh=True,plot_points=3)
                  plot17+=parametric_plot3d((s,tan(2)*s,t),(t,-scale,scale),(s,0,2),color="green",opacity=.25,mesh=True,plot_points=3)
                  plot17+=parametric_plot3d((cos(t),sin(t),0),(t,0,2),color="red",thickness=2)
                  plot17+=arrow3d((cos(2-0.1),sin(2-0.1),0),(cos(2),sin(2),0),color="orange",arrowsize=100)
                  plot17+=text3d("\u03B8=2",(1,2,0),color="red",fontsize=25)
                  plot17+=text3d("\u03B8=2+\u03C0",(-2,-1,0),color="orange",fontsize=25)
                  plot17+=parametric_plot3d((cos(t),sin(t),0),(t,0,pi+2),color="orange",thickness=1)+arrow3d((cos(a-0.1),sin(a-0.1),0),(cos(a),sin(a),0),color="red",arrowsize=100)
                  plot17+=text3d("\u03B8 with r \u003C 0",(3*cos(pi+2),3*sin(pi+2),5),color="green",fontsize=25)
                  plot17+=text3d("\u03B8 with r \u003E 0",(3*cos(2),3*sin(2),5),color="blue",fontsize=25)
                  show(plot17,aspect_ratio=1,viewpoint=[[-0.042,-0.5331,-0.845],172.39],camera_position=[3.3957,15.1258,7.5546])
                </slate>
              </interactive>
          </figure>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            In this example we will convert the elliptic paraboloid given by <m>z=x^2+y^2</m> to cylindrical coordinates. Algebraically, this is very simple because we can substitute <m>r^2=x^2+y^2</m> to get <m>z=r^2</m>. This should make sense for the graph of the elliptic paraboloid because the graph is rotationally symmetric around the <m>z</m>-axis (which comes from not having an explicit <m>\theta</m> dependence in the equation) and the height of the surface above the <m>xy</m>-plane increases quadratically as the location moves away from the <m>z</m>-axis.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="cylex4">
            <caption>A plot of <m>z=r^2</m> with segments for <m>r</m> in red and <m>z=r^2</m> in green</caption>
              <interactive title="interactive-cylex4" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
                <slate surface="sage">
