    <example>
      <task>
        <p>
          In this example we will look at converting equations and surfaces between rectangular and spherical coordinates. First, we will consider the surface defined by <m>\rho = 2</m>. Geometrically, we can think about <m>\rho =2</m> as the set of points that are two units away from the origin, which creates a sphere of radius 2. Algebraically, we can square both sides of our equation to get <m> \rho^2=4</m> and since <m>\rho^2=x^2+y^2+z^2</m>, the spherical coordinate equation <m>\rho =2</m> corresponds to the rectangular equation <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=4</m>. In fact, for all positive values of <m>k</m>, the surface <m>\rho =k</m> will be a sphere of radius <m>k</m>. 
        </p>
      </task>
      <task>
        <p>
          Next, we consider how to convert the equation of the half cone given by <m>z^2=2x^2+y^2</m> where <m>z \geq 0 </m> to spherical coordinates. Algebraically, we can use a couple of ideas from our conversion equations that include <m>z=\rho \cos(\phi)</m> and <m> r^2= \rho^2 \sin(\phi)^2</m>. Specifically, this means that
          <md>
            <mrow>z^2 =\amp 2x^2+2y^2</mrow>
            <mrow>z^2 =\amp 2\left(x^2+y^2\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\rho^2 \cos(\phi)^2=\amp 2\left(\rho^2 \sin(\phi)^2\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\tan(\phi)^2=\amp 2</mrow>
          </md>
          Since we are considering the part of the cone with <m>z \geq 0 </m>, we can use <m>\phi = \arctan(\sqrt{2})</m>. This should not be that suprising that half cones centered on the <m>z</m>-axis coorespond to a constant value of <m>\phi</m>. 
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="sphex12">
          <caption>A plot of the half cone <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=4</m> with measurement of <m>\phi</m> shown in orange</caption>
          <interactive title="interactive-sphex12" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
            <slate surface="sage">
              from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
              var('s,t')
              scale=2
              a=arctan(sqrt(2))
              plot22=axes(scale,1.5,color="black",frame=False)+text3d("x",(scale+0.5,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,scale+0.5,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,scale+0.5),fontsize=30)
              plot22+=parametric_plot3d((s*cos(t),s*sin(t),s/sqrt(2)),(s,0,2),(t,0,2*pi),color="red",opacity=0.65)
              plot22+=parametric_plot3d((0,sin(t),cos(t)),(t,0,a),color="blue",thickness=2)
              plot22+=text3d("\u03C6 \u2248 54.73",(1,1,1.3*cos(a/2)),color="blue",fontsize=25)
              plot22+=arrow3d((0,sin(a)-0.2,cos(a)+0.2),(0,sin(a),cos(a)),color="blue",width=10)
              show(plot22,viewpoint=[[-0.3347,-0.6698,-0.6628],143.35],camera_position=[7.4262,5.6364,1.1111])
            </slate>
            </interactive>
        </figure>
        <p>
          If we considered the bottom half of the cone given by <m>z^2=2x^2+y^2</m> where <m>z \leq 0 </m>, we would need to find the angle <m>\phi</m> between <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m> and <m>\pi</m> that satisfies <m>\tan(\phi)=\sqrt{2}</m>. Using complementary angles we see that the bottom half of the cone given by <m>z^2=2x^2+y^2</m> where <m>z \leq 0 </m> corresponds to the spherical equation <m>\phi = \pi - \arctan(\sqrt{2})</m>. 
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="sphex13">
          <caption>A plot of the botom half of the cone <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=4</m> with measurement of <m>\phi</m> shown in orange</caption>
          <interactive title="interactive-sphex13" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
            <slate surface="sage">
              from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
              var('s,t')
              scale=2
              a=pi-arctan(sqrt(2))
              plot23=axes(scale,1.5,color="black",frame=False)+text3d("x",(scale+0.5,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,scale+0.5,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,scale+0.5),fontsize=30)
              plot23+=parametric_plot3d((s*cos(t),s*sin(t),-s/sqrt(2)),(s,0,2),(t,0,2*pi),color="red",opacity=0.65,mesh=True,plot_points=20)
              plot23+=parametric_plot3d((0,sin(t),cos(t)),(t,0,a),color="blue")
              plot23+=arrow3d((0,sin(a)+0.1,cos(a)+0.2),(0,sin(a),cos(a)),color="blue",width=2)
              plot23+=text3d("\u03C6 \u2248 125.27",(0,2.5,0.25),color="blue",fontsize=25)
              show(plot23,viewpoint=[[-0.3297,-0.6865,-0.6481],145.43],camera_position=[7.854,6.3402,-0.0187])
            </slate>
          </interactive>
        </figure>
      </task>
      <task>
        <p> 
          Finally, we consider how to convert the plane given by <m>z=x+y</m> to spherical coordinates. We can use <m>x = \rho \sin(\phi) \cos(\theta)</m>, <m> y = \rho \sin(\phi) \sin(\theta)</m>, and <m> z = \rho \cos(\phi)</m> to get the following set of algebraic simplifications:
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>z =\amp x + y </mrow>
          <mrow>\rho \cos(\phi) =\amp \rho \cos(\theta) \sin(\phi)+ \rho \sin(\theta) \sin(\phi) </mrow>
          <mrow>\cos(\phi) =\amp \sin(\phi) \left( \cos(\theta) + \sin(\theta) \right) </mrow>
          <mrow> \tan(\phi) =\amp  \cos(\theta) + \sin(\theta) </mrow>
        </md>
        <p>
          If the graph of <m>\tan(\phi) =  \cos(\theta) + \sin(\theta)</m> seems unfamiliar, that is normal. This is not an expression you have (probably) seen before and does not simplify or offer geometric insight. This example shows how easily converting equations between coordinate systems without some geometric reasoning as to why can quickly turn into an exercise of algebra without much meaning. 
        </p>
      </task>
    </example>

